F WHOEVER MAY BE IN THE OFFICE. I NEED YOUR HELP PLEASE LET ME KNOW HOW TO GO ABOUT IT. www.joeministries.com ',0,'2011-12-08 06:34:51','2011-12-08 06:34:51'),(41,34,'Dear Sir/Madam,\r\n\r\nIn West Africa and Ghana in particular, seventy (70) percent of rural youth between the ages of 18 and 35 years are unemployed. This is basically due to poor quality education and inadequate infrastructure, as both factors significantly decrease school attendance motivation, resulting\r\n in very high drop-out rates and consequently high unemployment rates in rural communities in Ghana.  \r\n\r\nInterestingly, unemployed rural youth do not find hope in rural occupations such as animal and crop farming. Rather they prefer to migrate to sub-urban and urban communities in search of greener pastures. Having no employable skills to secure decent jobs, these talented and energetic migrants engage in all sorts of immoral acts such as cyber fraud, drug peddling, prostitution, thuggery, armed robbery just to survive.\r\n\r\nSir/Madam, though youth unemployment is a global challenge, the situation in Ghana is more searing. Available statistics indicate that one (1) out of every ten (10) unemployed rural youth engages in cyber fraud.\r\n\r\nRealizing that cyber fraud and other related youth crimes could have devastating consequences on Ghana and the world at large, a team of forward-thinking christian professionals brainstormed for innovative solutions to Ghana\'s rural youth unemployment menace. The results was the golden idea to establish Skills Colleges in all districts of the country, with the aim of providing unemployed rural youth with free skills training and job placement opportunities.\r\n\r\nAttempts to kick-start this noble initiative has been successful, with the first Skills College established in Awutu Obrachire, a rural community in the Awutu Senya district of the Central Region of Ghana. The Obrachire Campus offers a one (1) year free training in Catering, Cosmetology, and Mobile Phone Repair Technology. As resources unfold, the College will make available courses such as Dressmaking, I.C.T, and Mechanized Agriculture - just to mention a few. Currently the College has an enrollment of sixty-one (61) students, with as many as one hundred and six (106) students on our waiting list due to inadequate infrastructure, equipment and human resources.\r\n\r\nSince its inception in January 2010, the College has trained twenty -six (26) students who are now gainfully employed and contributing immensely to family strengthening and community development.\r\n\r\nSir/Madam, though the Skills College - Obrachire Campus is a potential youth employment provider for the Awutu Senya district, inadequate infrastructure, training equipment, tools, materials, furniture, products and human resources threaten enrollments. Consequently, we would be grateful if you could support us in any way convenient or relevant to your esteemed establishment. Please do not hesitate to contact us should you have any questions or concerns.\r\n\r\nWe are convinced that your generous support will help provide jobs for millions of jobless but energetic young men and women in Ghana\'s rural districts, improve the standard of living of rural families and promote sustainable socio-economic development of rural communities in Ghana.\r\n\r\nThanks in advance for your consideration of our request.\r\n\r\n\r\nSincerely,\r\n\r\nBernard Williams\r\n(Chief Executive Officer)\r\n\r\nP.O.Box GP 1865,\r\nAccra\r\nGhana\r\n\r\nTELEPHONE\r\n+233-(0)20-656-4490\r\n+233-(0)54-683-5333',0,'2011-12-09 11:05:19','2011-12-09 11:05:19'),(42,35,'I am writing to you because of my mother, sister and little brother hardship this season.  My mother just had back surgery this past august and money is very tight with her being out of work and because of her furnace and gas propane fireplace just going out.  My sister has been diagnosis with bi polar and lost her job last year and my little brother has down syndrome and always wants a good Christmas.  My father anniversary of his death on December 22 will be 5 years and would like to help them out as much as I can to give them a nice Christmas.  If you could help them this year or point me in the right direction it would be greatly appreciated.  We are not a family to ask for hand outs but I want some nice for them and if I could do it I would monetarily but I am tight also.  Thank you for your time in reading this and have a wonderful holiday.\r\nCollette Garrett 59\r\nSarah Garrett 30\r\nPatrick Garrett 23\r\n',0,'2011-12-09 16:53:30','2011-12-09 16:53:30'),(43,36,'hello my name is opal,\r\nme and my husband have been seperated and would like to reunite our family. we are both currently in different states. my question is is there anyway you could help us get a place to live here so we can be together. i am more than willing to work in your centers to pay you back. it is especially hard to be away from him and children during this time of year. if you could get back to me it would be greatly appreciated. i will do any work any hours to pay off any debt that this would entail.\r\nsincerly,\r\nopal cooke',0,'2011-12-09 18:39:46','2011-12-09 18:39:46'),(44,37,'A while back we received a flier about donating an animal or other things. I cannot find this and my children were wanting to pick something out to donate. We live on a farm so they can really connect with donating a farm animal. Can you help me?\r\nThanks for all you do for others. May God bless you all!\r\nHeidi Wettstein',0,'2011-12-09 20:12:02','2011-12-09 20:12:02'),(45,38,'I want to be grateful to God Almighty for CAM in Liberia. CAM is really touching the life of the poor people in my country Liberia by provided theirs physical and spiritual needs. CAM distribution have no discrimination in serving the people of Liberia, which include christian and the muslim religions.I have a friend by the name Federit Jones working with CAM in Liberia. I came to America t